most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenoviral conjunctivitis","Bacterial conjunctivitis","Allergic conjunctivitis","Fungal conjunctivitis","Herpes simplex blepharoconjunctivitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenoviral conjunctivitis. \u003C/strong\u003EThis is the most common cause of acute conjunctivitis in adults and presents with symptoms such as hyperaemia of the conjunctiva, watery discharge and a rapid onset of symptoms. It is often preceded by an upper respiratory tract infection. It is a highly contagious viral infection and can easily spread through close contacts or to the fellow eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is also a common cause of conjunctivitis and usually occurs unilaterally. It can present with similar symptoms but discharge is usually more purulent in nature compared to adenoviral conjunctivitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E will present with symptoms such as itching, burning and tearing along with ocular redness. Usually the discharge will be watery in nature. The lack of itching in this patients history make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare cause of conjunctivitis and is typically seen in immunocompromised patients. It is characterised by the presence of yellowish-white exudates on the conjunctiva and the symptoms usually progress over several days or weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex blepharoconjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E will present usually with vesicular eruptions on the eyelids or the conjunctiva along with ocular redness, discharge and tearing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adenoviral conjunctivitis is the most common cause of conjunctivitis and is highly contagious."],"references":["Tarabishy AB, Jeng BH. Bacterial conjunctivitis: a review for internists. Cleve Clin J Med. 2008 Jul;75(7):507-12. doi: 10.3949/ccjm.75.7.507. PMID: 18646586.","Hashmi MF, Gurnani B, Benson S. Conjunctivitis. 2022 Dec 6. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082078."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-20T09:22:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-20T09:22:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4834"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44489"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":